ould 'make no law respecting an establishment of religion, or prohibiting the free exercise thereof,' thus building a wall of separation between Church &amp; State.&quot; &#10;The supposed &quot;wall&quot; was to ensure that there was no state church, as in Europe, but was not to stop the public expression of religious beliefs, even in official state activies (e.g. swearing on a bible). &#10;Of course the sate church had existed throughout North America. In the Virginia colony it was the Church of England, in Massachusets it was the Puritan church, in Quebec the Roman Catholic Church, in Ontario it was the Church of England. &#10;The group in Toronto is not acting as a &quot;state church&quot;; it is a religous expression that is perfectly alowable under our Constutition. "/><type4:DocumentMetaData xmi:id="13" sofa="1" begin="0" end="1030" language="en" documentId="1367" isLastSegment="false"/><types:WebArgumentMetadata xmi:id="24" sofa="1" begin="0" end="0" author="Quinte Peregrine" docType="artcomment" origUrl="http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/toronto/tempers-flare-over-prayer-in-schools-1.1104775" topic="prayer-in-schools" thumbsUp="0" thumbsDown="0" origId="1367" notes="" title="Tempers flare over prayer in schools"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="39" sofa="1" begin="0" end="164"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="43" sofa="1" begin="165" end="450"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="47" sofa="1" begin="451" end="655"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="51" sofa="1" begin="656" end="894"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="55" sofa="1" begin="895" end="1030"/><cas:View sofa="1" members="13 24 39 43 47 51 55"/></xmi:XMI>